ased work of breathing","Inhibition of vagal afferents"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe sensation of dyspnoea involves multiple pathophysiological mechanisms:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulation of arterial chemoreceptors\u003C/strong\u003E by changes in blood gases (particularly increased carbon dioxide) directly triggers breathlessness\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased firing of pulmonary stretch receptors\u003C/strong\u003E actually reduces the sensation of dyspnoea - their activation contributes to normal breathing sensations\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced activation of respiratory muscles\u003C/strong\u003E would not cause dyspnoea - increased muscle work and fatigue contribute to breathlessness\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased work of breathing\u003C/strong\u003E would not cause dyspnoea - increased work of breathing is a key trigger\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of vagal afferents\u003C/strong\u003E would reduce rather than cause dyspnoea as these nerves help mediate the sensation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dyspnoea has multiple physiological triggers including chemoreceptor stimulation, increased work of breathing, and altered neural signaling.","Both central and peripheral mechanisms contribute to the sensation of breathlessness."],"references":["Ripamonti C, Bruera E. Dyspnea: pathophysiology and assessment. J Pain Symptom Manage. 1997 Apr;13(4):220-32. doi: 10.1016/s0885-3924(96)00327-2. PMID: 9136233.","Coccia CB, Palkowski GH, Schweitzer B, Motsohi T, Ntusi NA. Dyspnoea: Pathophysiology and a clinical approach. S Afr Med J. 2016 Jan;106(1):32-6. doi: 10.7196/samj.2016.v106i1.10324. PMID: 